throws at runtime.\" This suggests it's both a compiler and runtime upgrade.\n\nWith C# 14, the compiler would try to resolve `array.Contains(num)` inside the expression tree lambda. If C# 14 now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains` over `Enumerable.Contains` for arrays, and since expression trees can't use ref struct parameters, the compiler would emit an error.\n\nUnless... the C# 14 compiler is smart enough to fall back to `Enumerable.Contains` in expression tree contexts. But then there would be no issue.\n\nSo the real issue is probably that C# 14 changed overload resolution for extension methods, making `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` the preferred binding for arrays, which breaks expression tree compilation since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct and can't be used in expression trees. I think the most likely culprit is a breaking change in how C# 14 resolves the `Contains` method—the compiler now picks `MemoryExtensions.Contains` which operates on `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` instead of `Enumerable.Contains`, and since expression trees can't represent ref structs, the interpreter fails at runtime.\n\nThe workaround would be to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` or cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` first. But that would typically cause a compile-time error if the expression tree can't be built. Since the user reports a runtime failure, maybe the compiler still generates the expression tree somehow, but the interpreter chokes when it tries to execute it.\n\nI'm thinking this is likely a .NET 10 breaking change where the expression tree interpreter (`preferInterpretation: true`) encounters a `MethodCallExpression` it doesn't know how to handle—possibly because method resolution shifted from `Enumerable.Contains` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` for arrays in C# 14, and the interpreter doesn't support that newer method pattern. The expression tree gets created fine at compile time, but fails when the runtime tries to interpret it. The expression tree is built at runtime through reflection or manually, not compiled as a lambda by the compiler, which would explain why it throws at runtime rather than failing at compile time. Let me reconsider the actual code path—if the compiler resolves `array.Contains(num)` to a span-based `MemoryExtensions.Contains` method in C# 14, that would normally fail at compile time in an expression tree context, so either the compiler has special handling for this or the user is encountering the issue in a different scenario than I'm imagining.\n\nMaybe the compiler is smart enough to still pick `Enumerable.Contains` when building expression trees since they can't use ref structs, but then at runtime in .NET 10, `Enumerable.Contains` itself has been changed to internally call `MemoryExtensions.Contains`, and something about that new implementation breaks the expression tree interpreter—though that doesn't quite make sense since the interpreter just invokes methods through reflection and shouldn't care about internal implementations.\n\nI'm wondering if the breaking change isn't about method resolution at all, but rather about how C# 14 lowers certain expressions into expression tree nodes, and the expression tree interpreter in .NET 10 doesn't recognize or support these new node types.\n\nI think I should just go with the most likely explanation: C# 14 changed overload resolution so that `array.Contains(value)` now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains` with its `ReadOnlySpan<T>` parameter over `Enumerable.Contains`, and since ref structs can't be used in expression trees, this causes a failure either at compile time or runtime.\n\nThe fix is to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` or cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the older resolution path. But wait—the user said this throws at runtime, not at compile time, so maybe the expression tree is being constructed in a way that bypasses the compiler's normal checks. Let me think about what kind of expression tree would compile but fail at runtime when it tries to use the span-based overload.\n\nWhen `preferInterpretation: true` is set, the runtime interprets the expression tree node by node instead of JIT-compiling it, and the interpreter might not support implicit array-to-span conversions, which would cause a runtime exception. If `preferInterpretation: false` (the default), the JIT compiler might handle the span conversion fine. But actually, I'm not sure the C# compiler would even allow creating an expression tree that references `ReadOnlySpan<T>` in the first place, since ref structs have strict restrictions in expression trees. Let me reconsider what's actually happening here.\n\nI'm thinking the real issue might be that C# 14 introduced extension types with the `extension` keyword, which changed how overload resolution works for extension methods. Specifically, `MemoryExtensions.Contains` for `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` now takes precedence over `Enumerable.Contains`, and this change in method selection could be what's causing the behavior difference between .NET versions.\n\nWhen an array is passed to an expression tree, the compiler might select `MemoryExtensions.Contains` due to the implicit conversion to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, but the expression tree interpreter fails at runtime because it can't handle that conversion properly. The workaround would be to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` to disambiguate which method gets invoked.","outputTokens":4478,"requestId":"1428:13072B:24E482F:29A96EE:69EC0DF2"},"id":"8f1cd81e-dd2d-49c9-8e88-28ee3bce63b3","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:43:53.038Z","parentId":"ddd77e69-b2b3-4a4b-af57-5138ff3b4222"}
